    "review": [
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "K. Adams"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I know this post is old, but I want to recommend <a href=\"http://livingveniceblog.com/2009/09/venetian-spritz-recipe-or-once-ombra/\"> the Venetian white wine version</a> over the Gruppo Campari prosecco version. (In their defense, <a href=\"https://it.wikibooks.org/wiki/Libro_di_cucina/Ricette/Spritz\"> some areas in Tre Venezie use prosecco</a> in their spritz.) Stick with a still white wine, preferably a cheap table wine from the Veneto - pinot grigio is most available in the States. The prosecco version seems a bit too acidic and a bit too dry.\n\nIn a large, stemmed wine glass or a tall tumbler, add:\n1/3 white wine\n1/3 liquor (Aperol, Select, Campari, or Cynar)\n1/3 club soda\n2-3 ice cubes\ngarnish with 1-2 meaty green olives on a toothpick and a slice of lemon or orange"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "JV"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I prefer to add the prosecco last. Pouring it onto ice seems to decrease the fizz, which to me is part of the appeal of this drink."
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "duncan1205"
            },
            "reviewBody": "The Aperol spritz is delicious anytime of the year. We were having them as\npre-pre-dinner cocktails over Christmas and that extra little kick from the Prosecco and club soda is very lively ~ even in December! Love Compari and soda as well, but it is more of a warm weather drink for me; I guess I find the bitterness more refreshing. I also like Campari and orange in the summer"
        },
